1
00:00:01,161 --> 00:00:13,598
Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto samma-sambhodassa Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed, Noble and Fully Self-Awakened One.

2
00:00:14,778 --> 00:00:21,007
So this evening, the presentation is a little difficult because I've actually written something.

3
00:00:21,968 --> 00:00:27,995
So it's not going to be particularly verbatim, which is my normal

4
00:00:29,039 --> 00:00:30,701
way of presenting.

5
00:00:31,902 --> 00:00:32,543
So, okay.

6
00:00:33,445 --> 00:00:48,204
So in the last two talks, we looked at, first of all, the Buddha's victory verse and his naming of the house yoga, which is to say, of course, that deluded self, which is Mara.

7
00:00:48,243 --> 00:00:54,152
I mean, you know, when we talk about Mara, the evil tempter, that's the self, the deluded self.

8
00:00:56,308 --> 00:01:03,889
And then we went on, the next presentation was about a monk who wanted to know where all the world ended.

9
00:01:04,442 --> 00:01:10,632
And he tells him that this is badly phrased, that it should be where the world does not find a footing.

10
00:01:11,653 --> 00:01:21,730
And then he gives a very clear description, for want of a better word, of a place, of that place where the world does not find a footing.

11
00:01:22,510 --> 00:01:23,132
And this is it.

12
00:01:23,793 --> 00:01:27,759
There is a consciousness in which nothing is manifest.

13
00:01:28,600 --> 00:01:30,162
It has no boundary.

14
00:01:30,346 --> 00:01:32,490
and is full of light in all directions.

15
00:01:33,412 --> 00:01:36,438
So we can understand this to be a description of Nirvana.

16
00:01:39,105 --> 00:01:50,007
So now our task is to find a way to practice in such a way that this might become manifest to us.

17
00:01:51,170 --> 00:02:08,686
But before we do that, I'd like to offer these metaphors, these ways of thinking about what we're doing, so we can understand the process of liberating ourselves from self-deception, which is generated by this deluded self, this house builder.

18
00:02:10,407 --> 00:02:16,453
Now, some of you who've been to Saripanya to work with me have heard all this before, but I'm hoping that you've forgotten it.

19
00:02:17,133 --> 00:02:20,417
And if you haven't forgotten it, you'll excuse my...

20
00:02:20,987 --> 00:02:24,397
my presentation because I just wanted it to be in this medium.

21
00:02:26,663 --> 00:02:33,342
Okay, so the first metaphor, shall we say, is to recognise what happens to us when we're babies.

22
00:02:34,235 --> 00:02:37,682
It has a similarity to the process of insight meditation.

23
00:02:38,383 --> 00:02:45,118
For the first four months of our lives, it seems, we're bombarded by sensual information, can make no head or tail of it.

24
00:02:45,741 --> 00:02:53,457
But we do know when we're experiencing what is pleasant or unpleasant, that is the dual world that we enter into.

25
00:02:54,112 --> 00:03:04,629
Then around four months we start to delineate our first object out of this bewildering mass and in so doing we create the third dimension of depth.

26
00:03:04,930 --> 00:03:12,419
And it's usually out of this that we find our first object, our mother, our carer.

27
00:03:12,438 --> 00:03:20,168
And so the process continues, it seems, until around the age of three, we're pretty clear that I'm not anything outside my body.

28
00:03:20,768 --> 00:03:25,052
My body and my sense of me are separate from everyone and everything.

29
00:03:25,674 --> 00:03:28,858
And I know my toys belong to me.

30
00:03:29,198 --> 00:03:29,919
They're mine.

31
00:03:30,460 --> 00:03:34,144
A very strong sense of possession.

32
00:03:35,574 --> 00:03:44,217
There's still, of course, a great connection to Mother, but what we've done is we've distanced the outer world from the inner world.

33
00:03:46,492 --> 00:03:53,920
Our practice is to distance this inner world from the intuitive awareness .

34
00:03:54,622 --> 00:04:08,518
Every time we experience a feeling or sensation, an emotion or mood, a thought or an image as an object, we're telling ourselves that this cannot be the awareness that knows it.

35
00:04:08,497 --> 00:04:18,423
The knower, the feeler, the experiencer experiences itself as quite other to everything it knows, feels and experiences.

36
00:04:20,817 --> 00:04:32,769
Now that's what happens when we turn everything into an object, just as the baby creates a third dimension by reaching out and so creating distance.

37
00:04:33,048 --> 00:04:40,596
So we're pushing away as it, so to speak, what we are overwhelmed with, our sensations, feelings, and thoughts.

38
00:04:41,317 --> 00:04:48,444
And that distance between the object and the awareness is the inner third dimension.

39
00:04:52,002 --> 00:04:55,427
Now, the second metaphor that I like to use is one of Narcissus.

40
00:04:56,129 --> 00:04:59,533
Now, as you remember, Narcissus was a handsome, beautiful young man.

41
00:05:00,134 --> 00:05:09,230
And he looked into the pool, caught the image of his own face, fell in love with it, and then went to embrace it and fell in and drowned.

42
00:05:09,730 --> 00:05:15,360
Now, this is understood as a myth about self-absorption, pride, vanity, conceit.

43
00:05:16,927 --> 00:05:24,937
And water in mythology often represents, well, a lot of things, but life and creation, as well as chaos and purification.

44
00:05:27,639 --> 00:05:29,742
However, we can read this myth spiritually.

45
00:05:32,105 --> 00:05:42,158
It is that sati, the intuitive awareness, IA notice, not AI, that catches its image on the screen of consciousness.

46
00:05:43,184 --> 00:05:48,589
Consciousness itself is that screen upon which the six senses manifest.

47
00:05:49,831 --> 00:05:59,682
That is why consciousness is defined by the sense base, eye consciousness, ear consciousness, mind consciousness, and so on.

48
00:05:59,702 --> 00:06:06,490
So every morning we wake up, the first thing we are aware of is ourselves, our self-awareness.

49
00:06:07,432 --> 00:06:12,937
I'm sure you'll have had the experience of waking up in an unfamiliar room at a hotel or friends.

50
00:06:13,357 --> 00:06:19,627
And for those first few seconds you can't recognize where you are and so who you are.

51
00:06:20,149 --> 00:06:23,535
There's a momentary panic till we situate ourselves.

52
00:06:24,896 --> 00:06:35,916
So it is that sati sees itself, senses itself in the pool of the mind, the pool of the world that the mind is creating, and then we drown in it.

53
00:06:37,379 --> 00:06:38,300
However,

54
00:06:38,720 --> 00:06:46,829
the Buddha has come to the rescue and offered us a methodology to resuscitate us, ourselves.

55
00:06:47,872 --> 00:06:53,177
We must drag Narcissus out of the water, sitting back on the bank of the pool.

56
00:06:53,738 --> 00:07:07,055
And so it is that in Vipassana, we draw our awareness out of the body and mind with its feelings, perceptions and habits, and we experience ourselves as the one who knows.

57
00:07:09,567 --> 00:07:15,656
Now in this, our basic identity begins to change, where we base our identity.

58
00:07:16,718 --> 00:07:24,812
As children, our identity is very body-centered, and we have that experience when we bite our tongues when we're eating.

59
00:07:25,733 --> 00:07:33,245
Just for that singular moment of the stabbing pain, we're absorbed into it and become a physical self.

60
00:07:33,800 --> 00:07:41,848
We then very quickly bounce out of it and are annoyed with ourselves and so become an emotional self.

61
00:07:42,668 --> 00:07:47,473
We then might reflect upon it and counsel ourselves to eat more slowly and mindfully.

62
00:07:47,514 --> 00:07:50,117
And so we become a thinking self.

63
00:07:51,619 --> 00:07:55,742
But this position of the observer, the feeler, transcends them all.

64
00:07:56,184 --> 00:08:02,170
It can be aware of all the experiences the body and heart-mind have.

65
00:08:04,714 --> 00:08:10,922
Then we might acknowledge more and more clearly the distinction between the object and the subject.

66
00:08:12,223 --> 00:08:18,529
So this takes us back to the distancing, the disidentifying process of the baby and young child.

67
00:08:19,612 --> 00:08:27,560
And this takes us a step further to investigate the nature of this identity of the self as the observer and the feeler.

68
00:08:29,122 --> 00:08:33,506
For having accessed within ourselves this inner position,

69
00:08:33,672 --> 00:08:43,647
called by Jnana Ponnikartera in his classic work, still worthy of a read, The Heart of Buddhist Meditation, an observation post.

70
00:08:44,087 --> 00:09:01,653
And from this observation post, we can see clearly that the body and heart, heart-mind, the emotions and thought life, continue of themselves without the engagement of this self-awareness that we now experience ourselves to be.

71
00:09:04,097 --> 00:09:15,174
Now we have a situation where the self-awareness sees the body as other and that the body keeps on being the body with its sensations and feelings.

72
00:09:15,936 --> 00:09:22,905
The emotions and moods still continue to arise and the thoughts and images continue to flit across the mind.

73
00:09:24,187 --> 00:09:32,721
None of it needing the direct control of sati, this intuitive awareness.

74
00:09:32,953 --> 00:09:37,503
So we're left with the question as to the nature of this self-awareness.

75
00:09:39,206 --> 00:09:45,477
So our investigation now turns towards the self-awareness, that sense of presence.

76
00:09:46,961 --> 00:09:51,149
Since we're aware of it, that makes it an object.

77
00:09:51,168 --> 00:09:52,751
So we can't be it.

78
00:09:53,643 --> 00:10:11,196
worse we realize that this identity is the very portal into the world manufactured by the six senses the five physical senses and the heart mind this is the face in the pool

79
00:10:11,462 --> 00:10:25,940
Indeed, this primary self is Mara, the evil tempter, inviting us into the pleasures and joys of the world, only to find ourselves entangled, ensnared and imprisoned.

80
00:10:27,481 --> 00:10:36,491
This is the house builder the Buddha discovered to be the agent of rebirth, the root of all our discontent and suffering.

81
00:10:38,107 --> 00:10:42,400
So now there's a practice which is pretty specific to this investigation.

82
00:10:44,808 --> 00:10:51,730
And I'm indebted, well, we are indebted to the Mahayana school for this.

83
00:10:52,250 --> 00:11:10,052
When the body is very still and the heart calm and the mind is silent, now admittedly that's pretty rare in our daily lives, though it does arise on retreat, we can raise our attention into that feeling of presence located in the forehead.

84
00:11:11,355 --> 00:11:16,721
We can stay there to the exclusion of everything else and again just gaze.

85
00:11:17,714 --> 00:11:24,962
We now know because we are aware of that sense of self, it is an object and therefore belongs to the mind.

86
00:11:26,104 --> 00:11:34,433
So it must be arising and passing away, even though it seems to be coexistent with the awareness that knows it.

87
00:11:36,196 --> 00:11:44,346
Remember, consciousnesses are flashing at enormous speeds so that they give us a sense of continuity.

88
00:11:45,187 --> 00:11:53,860
We need to hold that position as best we can without straining, just gazing with wonder.

89
00:11:55,623 --> 00:11:59,587
Is that sense of self arising and passing away?

90
00:12:01,932 --> 00:12:02,572
That is all.

91
00:12:03,214 --> 00:12:05,817
Just to gaze with wonder.

92
00:12:06,938 --> 00:12:11,346
Presume that the awareness knows what it's looking for.

93
00:12:14,076 --> 00:12:16,802
So that's one particular technique.

94
00:12:18,144 --> 00:12:22,734
The other one, of course, is the one that we usually use when we're practicing Vipassana.

95
00:12:25,278 --> 00:12:31,191
And that involves directly investigating the process of impermanence.

96
00:12:31,913 --> 00:12:42,730
So whenever we see an object, whether it's a sensation or a feeling, mood or emotion, thought or image appearing and disappearing, the same applies.

97
00:12:43,412 --> 00:12:54,090
The sati, this observer, this feeler, that experiences the object arising and passing away, cannot itself be arising and passing away.

98
00:12:54,644 --> 00:13:13,327
That gap, minute as it is, between the passing of an object and the arising of another, would also constitute a glimpse into our true nature, which is unborn, undying, uncreated and unconditioned.

99
00:13:15,147 --> 00:13:37,307
so we can sum up the techniques by first of all pulling away from the objects we're aware of so it becomes something to observe and feel remembering that the perceiver cannot be the perceived this is the first step of not me not mine not self then

100
00:13:37,456 --> 00:13:49,467
The direct experience of the appearance and disappearance of the object allows sati to experience itself as other, whole, entire and permanent.

101
00:13:50,769 --> 00:14:03,581
Slowly but surely, this intuitive awareness, satipañña, becomes an island unto itself, impervious to the physical and mental worlds.

102
00:14:04,404 --> 00:14:28,049
this is where the very world cannot find a footing now fortunately we have an example of someone who describes what it's like to be fully liberated from the delusion of self and this actually warrants a talk but for our present purpose it's enough to quote her

103
00:14:29,160 --> 00:14:39,914
I'm presuming for the time being that you know the categories that the Buddha teaches, the four great elements, the six sense bases and the five aggregates.

104
00:14:41,437 --> 00:14:52,130
Meichi Kyo was an ordinary, barely educated village girl who died in 1991 at the age of 90.

105
00:14:53,592 --> 00:14:55,455
And this is her statement.

106
00:14:58,725 --> 00:15:06,499
Body, mind and essence are all distinct and separate realities.

107
00:15:08,642 --> 00:15:10,565
Absolutely everything is known.

108
00:15:11,787 --> 00:15:15,472
Earth, water, fire and wind.

109
00:15:17,176 --> 00:15:22,945
Body, feeling, memory, thought and consciousness.

110
00:15:23,649 --> 00:15:30,456
sounds, sights, smells, tastes and touches and emotions.

111
00:15:32,097 --> 00:15:43,948
Anger, greed and delusion, all are known, I know them all as they exist in their own natural states.

112
00:15:45,549 --> 00:15:50,754
But no matter how much I'm exposed to them,

113
00:15:51,105 --> 00:15:59,014
I am unable to detect even an instant when they have any power over my heart.

114
00:16:00,255 --> 00:16:10,268
They arise and cease, they're forever changing, but the presence that knows them never changes for an instant.

115
00:16:10,288 --> 00:16:13,711
It is forever unborn and undying.

116
00:16:14,572 --> 00:16:17,855
This is the end of all suffering.

117
00:16:21,245 --> 00:16:40,501
I can only hope my little homily has been of interest, and that by your dedication to the practice you will be liberated from all suffering, like Mei-Chi Kiao, sooner rather than later.

